<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"  xml:id="chap_transformation_matrix">
  <title>The Matrix of a Linear Transformation</title>
  <introduction>
    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          By the end of this section, you should be able to give precise and thorough answers to the
          questions listed below. You may want to keep these questions in mind to focus your thoughts as
          you complete the section.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            How do we represent a linear transformation from <m>\R^n</m> to <m>\R^m</m> as a matrix transformation?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            How can we represent any linear transformation from a finite dimensional vector space <m>V</m> to a finite dimensional vector space <m>W</m> as a matrix transformation?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            In what ways is representing a linear transformation as a matrix transformation useful?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>
